Key Match Events: Pakistan overcame a top-order batting hiccup with sharp pace bowling to beat the Netherlands by 81 runs.
Bas de Leede picked up 4-62 with his seam bowling to bowl out Pakistan for 286.
De Leede then kept the Netherlands in the chase with a knock of 67 off 68 balls.
Haris Rauf picked up 3-43, Shaheen Afridi claimed 1-37, and Hasan Ali bagged 2-37.
Vikramjit Singh made a fighting 52 off 67 balls and combined in a 70-run stand with de Leede.
Rauf took the wickets of Teja Nidamanuru and Scott Edwards in the space of three balls.
Saud Shakeel and Mohammad Rizwan scripted Pakistan’s revival with a 120-run partnership.
Shakeel scored 68 off 52 balls and Rizwan made 68 off 75 balls.
Nawaz (39) and Shadab (32) played little cameos to lift the total while tailenders Afridi and Rauf also added 19 runs for the last wicket.
Post-Match Reflections: Pakistan skipper Babar Azam credited the bowlers for starting well and taking wickets in the middle overs.
Saud Shakeel expressed that nerves were there as they had lost three wickets, but he was lucky to get early boundaries.
Netherlands captain Scott Edwards found it disappointing but praised de Leede’s innings.
Miscellaneous Highlights: The Netherlands qualified for the World Cup with a dramatic Super Over win over the West Indies.
Out-of-form Fakhar Zaman offered a tame return catch to van Beek.
World’s top-ranked ODI batter Babar had an unusual struggle for 18 balls in scoring 5 runs before getting out.
